  "expressions": {
    "list": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "id": "101",
        "text": "This graph demonstrates the conjectured result of Driori and Teboull (2012, https://arxiv.org/pdf/1206.3209), later proven by Kim (2025, https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.04427) that the best step size for a fixed-step gradient descent method is the value of \"h\" which satisfies (1 - h)^2N = 1/(2Nh + 1).\n\nThat is, considering the worst-case performance over all smooth, convex functions, the \"best worst-case performance\" occurs when the stepsize solves that equation above.\n\nThis Desmos graph lets you play around with various parameters, like the smoothness of the class, the initial distance to optimal, the number of steps taken, and lastly the stepsize.\n\nRemarkably, this (inherently difficult problem) of finding the worst case performance over all possible functions simplifies to just looking at the performance of two functions: a quadratic and a Huber. So we analyze gradient descent with a fixed step size on just those two, and see which is worse. The conjectures result says that when these equal, the optimal step size is attained. "
      },
      {
        "type": "folder",
        "id": "28",
        "title": "Huber Function and Points",
        "inFrontOfEverything": true,
        "collapsed": true
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "1",
        "folderId": "28",
        "color": "#c74440",
        "latex": "h_{uber}\\left(x\\right)\\ =\\ \\left\\{\\left|x\\right|\\le t_{1}:\\ \\frac{L}{2}x^{2},\\ \\ \\left|x\\right|>t_{1}:\\ Lt_{1}\\left(\\left|x\\right|-\\frac{t_{1}}{2}\\right)\\right\\}",
        "lineWidth": "5"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "8",
        "folderId": "28",
        "color": "#6042a6",
        "latex": "h_{quad}\\left(x\\right)\\ =\\ \\frac{L}{2}x^{2}\\ \\left\\{\\left|x\\right|\\le t_{1}\\right\\}",
        "lineWidth": "5"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "17",
        "folderId": "28",
        "color": "#2d70b3",
        "latex": "h_{linear}\\left(x\\right)\\ =\\ \\ Lt_{1}\\left(\\left|x\\right|-\\frac{t_{1}}{2}\\right)\\ \\left\\{\\left|x\\right|>t_{1}\\right\\}",
        "lineWidth": "5"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "5",
        "folderId": "28",
        "color": "#000000",
        "latex": "\\left(R,h_{uber}\\left(R\\right)\\right)",
        "dragMode": "NONE",
        "pointSize": "20",
        "movablePointSize": "20"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "19",
        "folderId": "28",
        "color": "#2d70b3",
        "latex": "I\\ =\\left[0,1,2,...,N\\right]"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "id": "30",
        "folderId": "28",
        "text": "This generates all the points from gradient descent on the Huber function, since each gradient will be the same (it always stays on the linear part)"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "26",
        "folderId": "28",
        "color": "#6042a6",
        "latex": "X_{huber}\\ =\\ R\\ -\\ \\frac{hI}{L}h_{uber}'\\left(R\\right)"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "31",
        "folderId": "28",
        "color": "#2d70b3"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "32",
        "folderId": "28",
        "color": "#6042a6",
        "latex": "\\left(X_{huber},\\ h_{uber}\\left(X_{huber}\\right)\\right)",
        "pointSize": "12",
        "movablePointSize": "12"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "33",
        "folderId": "28",
        "color": "#6042a6"
      },
      {
        "type": "folder",
        "id": "34",
        "title": "Quadratic Function and Points",
        "inFrontOfEverything": true,
        "collapsed": true
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "16",
        "folderId": "34",
        "color": "#fa7e19",
        "latex": "q_{uad}\\left(x\\right)\\ =\\ \\frac{L}{2}x^{2}",
        "lineWidth": "5"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "id": "36",
        "folderId": "34",
        "text": "Here, we have to use a recursion to generate the gradient steps, but below are the points generate by the algorithm for the quadratic function"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "38",
        "folderId": "34",
        "color": "#000000",
        "latex": "\\left(R,q_{uad}\\left(R\\right)\\right)",
        "dragMode": "NONE",
        "pointSize": "20",
        "movablePointSize": "20"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "37",
        "folderId": "34",
        "color": "#c74440",
        "latex": "\\left(X_{quad},\\ q_{uad}\\left(X_{quad}\\right)\\right)",
        "pointSize": "12",
        "movablePointSize": "12"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "25",
        "folderId": "34",
        "color": "#388c46",
        "latex": "X_{quad}\\ =\\ g_{step}\\left(I\\right)"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "22",
        "folderId": "34",
        "color": "#000000",
        "latex": "g_{step}\\left(N\\right)=g_{step}\\left(N-1\\right)\\ -\\ \\frac{h}{L}q_{uad}'\\left(g_{step}\\left(N-1\\right)\\right)"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "23",
        "folderId": "34",
        "color": "#c74440",
        "latex": "g_{step}\\left(0\\right)=R"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "74",
        "color": "#c74440"
      },
      {
        "type": "folder",
        "id": "63",
        "title": "Quadratic GD Lines (optional, if you want to view click the circle next to the folder drop down to highlight the directions the iterates are moving to)",
        "collapsed": true
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "64",
        "folderId": "63",
        "color": "#c74440",
        "latex": "y=q_{uad}\\left(X_{quad}\\left[i\\right]\\right)+\\frac{q_{uad}\\left(X_{quad}\\left[i\\right]\\right)-q_{uad}\\left(X_{quad}\\left[i+1\\right]\\right)}{\\left(X_{quad}\\left[i\\right]\\right)-\\left(X_{quad}\\left[i+1\\right]\\right)}\\left(x-X_{quad}\\left[i\\right]\\right)\\ \\left\\{\\left|x-\\frac{X_{quad}\\left[i+1\\right]+X_{quad}\\left[i\\right]}{2}\\right|\\le\\left|\\frac{X_{quad}\\left[i+1\\right]-X_{quad}\\left[i\\right]}{2}\\right|\\right\\}\\operatorname{for}\\ i\\ =\\ \\left[1,...,N\\right]\\ ",
        "lineStyle": "DOTTED",
        "lineWidth": "1"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "65",
        "folderId": "63",
        "color": "#388c46"
      },
      {
        "type": "folder",
        "id": "67",
        "title": "Huber GD Lines (optional, if you want to view click the circle next to the folder drop down to highlight the directions the iterates are moving to)"
      },
      {
        "type": "expression",
        "id": "69",
        "folderId": "67",
        "color": "#6042a6",
        "latex": "\\left(\\frac{X_{huber}\\left[i\\right]+X_{huber}\\left[i+1\\right]}{2}+R_{t}\\cos\\left(t\\right),\\frac{h_{uber}\\left(X_{huber}\\left[i\\right]\\right)+h_{uber}\\left(X_{huber}\\left[i+1\\right]\\right)}{2}+R_{t}\\sin\\left(t\\right)\\right)\\ \\left\\{\\arctan\\left(h_{uber}'\\left(X_{huber}\\left[i\\right]\\right)\\right)<t<\\arctan\\left(h_{uber}'\\left(X_{huber}\\left[i\\right]\\right)\\right)+\\pi\\right\\}\\operatorname{for}\\ i\\ =\\ \\left[1,...,\\ N\\right]",
        "lineStyle": "DOTTED",
        "parametricDomain": {
          "min": "0",
          "max": "6"
        },
        "lineWidth": "1",
        "domain": {
          "min": "0",
          "max": "6"
        }
